\section*{Chapter 7}

\section*{Network typicality}

\section*{7.1 Problem formulation}

\textbf{Meta-problem:}

Given:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Network/graph $G_0$, and
    \item Network/graph model $P(G)$.
\end{enumerate}

Find: whether $G_0$ is typical in $P(G)$.

\textbf{Real problem:}

What is a useful definition of \textit{typicality}?

\textbf{Real answer:}

A definition of typicality is useful if it allows one to state anything formal concerning any properties of $G_0$ that make no formal sense for any given $G_0$ (e.g., sparsity, small-worldness, strong clustering, scale-freeness) based on the corresponding properties of the model $P(G)$, where they do make perfect formal sense. Informally, in short, we would like to ``link'' $G_0$ to $P(G)$ (by saying that $\sim$``$G_0$ comes from $P(G)$''), and switch our attention to $P(G)$.

\textbf{Disclaimers:}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item One of the most confusing points in network science:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item With high probability, a typical network scientist believes they know a simple solution to this problem;
        \item With high probability, they don't!
    \end{itemize}
    \item The underlying assumption is that $P(G)$ is known, but in most cases $P(G)$ is intractable (e.g., in preferential attachment).
    \item $n$ is fixed! (since $G_0$ is fixed)
\end{enumerate}

\vfill

\begin{center}
26
\end{center}

