% ===== Page 5 =====
\section*{7.7 Typical graph}

Let $P(G) = P[f(G)]$. \hfill (A.2)

\textbf{Example:} in $\mathcal{G}(n,p)$, $P(G) = p^{m(G)}(1-p)^{\alpha' - m(G)} = \tilde{P}[m(G)]$.

Observe that if A.2 holds, then $P(G_1) = P(G_2)$ if $f(G_1) = f(G_2)$.
\textbf{Definition:} If A.2 holds, then $f$ is called a \emph{sufficient statistics}.
(To know $P(G)$, it suffices to know $f(G)$.)

\textbf{Definition 7.6.} (not bad at all)

\fbox{If A.1 and A.2 hold, then $G_0$ is $\varepsilon$-typical in $P(G)$ if it is $(f,\varepsilon)$-typical according to Definition 7.3.}

Definition 7.6 is not bad at all, because:
\begin{itemize}
\item since we know that $f$ concentrates (A.1) and that $P(G) = \tilde{P}[f(G)]$ (A.2), we also know that a bulk of the $P(G)$ probability mass is concentrated on graphs that have values of property $f$ close to $\bar{f}$;
\item if $f(G_0)$ is not close to $\bar{f}$, then such $G_0$ is far away from the peak, so it is an atypical outlier.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Examples:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Any $G_0$ with $2m/n = \bar{k} \in [\mathbb{E}\{\bar{k}\} - \varepsilon, \mathbb{E}\{\bar{k}\} + \varepsilon]$, where $\bar{k} = p(n-1)$, is typical in $\mathcal{G}(n,p)$.
\item In particular, any such $G_0$ with a scale-free degree distribution is still a typical ER graph.
\item Its degree distribution is atypical, but this does not matter in $\mathcal{G}(n,p)$!
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Meditation exercise:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Generate a PA graph with $\gamma = 3$, average degree $\bar{k} = 10$, and size $n = 10^6$.
\item Meditate that:
\begin{itemize}
\item You \emph{cannot} be sure that the generated graph is a typical PA graph.
\item You \emph{can} be sure that the generated graph is a typical ER graph in $\mathcal{G}(n,p)$ with $n = 10^6$ and $p \approx \bar{k}/n = 10^{-5}$.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\textbf{This is because:}
\begin{itemize}
\item All graphs with $\bar{k} = 10$ are equally likely and comprise a bulk of the probability mass in this $\mathcal{G}(n,p)$.
\item The number of graphs with the binomial degree distribution in this typical set is much larger than the number of graphs with other degree distributions, including power-law distributions.
\item This entropic domination makes the binomial distribution to be a typical value of the degree distribution property in $G(n,p)$.
\item But $P(G)$ in $\mathcal{G}(n,p)$ ``does not care'' about the degree distribution; it ``cares'' only about the average degree.
\end{itemize}

\fbox{Typical network $\neq$ typical value of a network property!}

\vspace{1em}

If A.2 does not hold (e.g., in PA), then there is no good definition of a typical network :(

But there is always a good definition of a typical sequence of networks! :)

\vspace{2em}

\begin{center}
30
\end{center}

